Study Information Sheet and Consent Form 

 

University of California, Berkeley

 

Understanding the Decision Making of Evacuees

 

Doctoral student Stephen Wong (with Professor Susan Shaheen and Professor Joan Walker), from the Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering at the University of California, Berkeley (UC Berkeley), is conducting a research project.  You are invited to participate in this study because of your experience in the recent evacuation process for the recent disaster. The researchers will be obtaining your consent for this project.

 

Why is this study being done?

Disasters have a major impact on the built environment and many situations require the movement of people away from harm to reduce risk and ensure human safety.  This evacuation of people is an integral part of emergency management plans.  Despite advances in transportation management strategies, evacuations continue to cause congested conditions on transportation networks.  At the same time, vulnerable populations frequently lack adequate resources for evacuation and sheltering, and a large proportion of the population do not comply with evacuation orders.  As part of this study, we are analyzing how individuals make decisions after receiving a mandatory or recommended evacuation order. 

 

What will happen if I take part in this research study?

We will ask you survey questions related to your experience with evacuating or not evacuating your residence during the last disaster.  These questions will include demographic information about you and your household, the address of your household, the choices you made during the event, and your opinions on the use of sharing economy platforms (i.e., technology platforms that allow the sharing of goods such as transportation and housing). If the survey includes questions you do not wish to or cannot answer, you may either choose to skip those questions, or you may choose not to participate in the study. All pieces of personal information and personal information of others will be kept as confidential as possible. Only one member from each immediate household may take the survey. You may fill out the survey at a time and place of your choosing.

 

How long will I be in the research study?

The survey will take approximately 20 minutes.

 

Are there any potential benefits if I participate?

Participants will not directly benefit from the research.  However, the results of the research may contribute to an improved understanding of individualsâ€™ decision making in disaster situations. 

 

Will I be compensated for my time?

A participant will be entered into a drawing if the participant 1) completes the survey, and 2) provides an email address or home address. These individuals will be eligible to win 1 of 5 VISA Gift Cards valued at $200 each. The drawing will take place when the last survey is received. For any drawing, the odds of winning depend on how many people have a ticket entered in the drawing. As we do not know how many people will participate in this study-related drawing, we cannot predict what will be the odds of winning a prize. Individuals who win will be sent the gift cards within two weeks of the drawing through email or through their physical home address.

 

Are there any other parts to this research?

You will have the opportunity to indicate if you are interested in being a part of a focus group. Only individuals who mark their interest in a focus group AND provide an email address, telephone number, or physical address will be eligible. When the surveys are completed, individuals will be chosen at random to participate in a focus group. If you are chosen, you will be contacted within 3 months from the end of the surveys.

 

Are there any potential risks or discomforts that I can expect from this study?

If you experienced stress or anxiety during the evacuation process, you may remember some of these feelings and you may find it uncomfortable to answer certain questions.  However, the questions are phrased to minimize any lasting negative effects. There is also a risk of a breach of confidentiality. This will risk has been minimized by using encrypted password-protected data storage and by omitting exact street addresses in any publications or reports on the research.

 

 



Will information about me and my participation be kept confidential?

Your information will be kept as confidential as possible.  Confidentiality will be maintained by using encrypted password-protected data storage on the web.  Only the primary researchers will have access to this data. Participants should close the webpage after they have finished the survey in order to protect their privacy. Confidentiality cannot be guaranteed since data will be transmitted online and data will be stored online.

 

How long will data be retained?

Data will be retained for at most three years after the last survey has been conducted.

 

What are my rights if I take part in this study?

Â·       You can choose whether or not you want to be in this study, and you may withdraw your consent and discontinue participation at any time.

Â·       Whatever decision you make, there will be no penalty to you or loss of benefits to which you are otherwise entitled.

Â·       You may refuse to answer any questions that you do not want to answer and still remain in the study.

 

Whom can I contact if I have questions about this study?

Â·       The research team:  

If you have any questions, comments or concerns about the research, you can talk to one of the researchers. Please contact: 

 

Susan Shaheen, Professor (Faculty Sponsor)

sashaheen@tsrc.berkeley.edu or 510-642-9168

joanwalker@berkeley.edu or 510-642-6897

stephen.wong@berkeley.edu or 330-998-4533

If you have any questions or concerns about your rights and treatment as a research subject, you may contact the office of UC Berkeley's Committee for the Protection of Human Subjects, at 510-642-7461 or subjects@berkeley.edu or write to:

Q81:
As much as I hate FL's Governor Scott, HE and the state did a fantastic job.  Their messages were clear and concise.  This was a big f'ing hurricane and it was heading right up the center of the state and the potential for catastrophic damage was huge.  That was very clear and made clear.  Their planning paid off.  

Highway Patrol did an impressive job of keeping the roads flowing.  I made it in 1.5 hrs for the evacuation.  FHP had two troopers and a tow truck on every single disabled vehicle I saw as I headed north.   They should be proud of how they did -- it was a phenomenal response. 

I wanted to evacuate on Wednesday/Thursday to beat the traffic, but according to Google Maps' traffic indications, many other people had the same idea.  So I waited an extra night, watching the traffic maps.  From past experience, people don't evacuate between 10pm-9am.  My hunches were confirmed by Google Maps.  So on Friday at 3am, I got in my car, swung by the office for one time, and headed north.   It was by-far the fastest I've ever made it from Fort Myers to St. Petersburg.  It normally takes 2.25 hours normally, >3+ hours with rush hour traffic.  

Interestingly, this was the storm path emergency managers had always feared.  To the point that it didn't get discussed often.  I worked in the media at one point in my life and asked what were the plans if a storm came right up the center of the state.  "Pray it doesn't....You can't evacuate the entire state" is what I was told.   Statistically, it was unlikely, so we generally didn't plan for this pathway.  

Really, the only issues I came across were shortages of bottled water and bread.  Why people gravitate towards these things in an emergency is beyond me.  Wine and non-perishable foods work just as well if not better.   There were sporadic fuel shortages, but if one station was out, there was usually another down the road which still had fuel.  Fuel deliveries were constant.

Q81:
6 Million people were ordered to evacuate their homes in Florida. Every five minutes there was a new area of the state under a mandatory evacuation. As much as Governor Scott did to help, it still was not enough. There were fuel shortages a week prior to the storm as well as a shortage of supplies. 
There needs to be better communication to those who live in flood prone areas well ahead of a storm. Do not have us rushing around buying supplies to "hunker down" in place only to be told one day ahead of the storm to "get out." 
This was the worst situation I have seen in Florida in 22 years. People running around like animals just to top off their tanks when people who really needed gas had to hope they could make the next station. It is bad enough that in SW Florida, you may have to drive for 20 miles before the next exit and hope there is even one gas station at that exit that has fuel. At times, I-75 and I-95 were a parking lot. It was taking people hours to go just a few miles.

Q81:
The vast majority of residents were not under mandatory evacuation orders.  Those who live more inland were not required to evacuate.  (I live approximately 4-5 miles inland, and was not required to evacuate.)  The recommended "everyone evacuate" order was truly impractical, because there would have been nowhere for all of us to go, and so much traffic if we all had actually left that we would have been at a standstill, and risked being in a more dangerous situation in a car when the storm actually hit.  Plus, I have pets that I would not leave behind.

It is difficult to express to those not living here the high degree of uncertainty that came with Hurricane Irma and its landfall location.  Up until the day before landfall, there was still question about which Florida coast would be the landfall point.  Also, regardless of which coast was hit, the storm was expected to travel up the entire state.  Florida's geography, being one long penninsula, makes it difficult to evacuate the state altogether.  It is an 8-hour drive north with zero traffic (with really only a couple of highways to choose from) in order to leave the state from southern Florida.  Traffic during an evacuation makes that trip substantially longer, with no gas or shelter locations along the way.  The size of Hurricane Irma, and the uncertainty of landfall location, ruled out East-West evacuation to the other coast.  

Many who live here work in the healthcare industry, as I do (I'm a nurse).  We were required to be at work in the hospital, or risk being fired.  Not everyone can just leave.  Even if we had all left, it would be almost impossible to get back after the storm in a timely manner, because everyone else would be doing the same thing.

Q81:
There is such a long period of time between when a storm becomes a topic of discussion and when it actually arrives here, there is storm fatigue.  With Irma, there was more than a week of hearing about Harvey -- and then all the build up to Irma.  The news stations are focused on it constantly.  At some point, people stopped listening until a few days before the storm.  With the shifting pattern of where the storm would go, there was a lot of uncertainty -- that played out as panic at the grocery stores and gasoline stations.  There was a lack of just bringing in gasoline trucks prior to the power going out.  If supply had been consistent, everyone could have gotten what they needed -- but as it worked out -- people were hoarding because of panic.
We didn't leave because one of us had to work during the storm as a local government employee --- and we were concerned after hearing horror stories from friends who left and could then not find hotels or gasoline on the trip.  The thought of what the trip back would be like was also a concern.

Q81: I know there is no sure way to accurately gauge the path of an approaching hurricane, there was no need for the media, especially local news stations to get people worked into a frenzy. People were buying way more water than they actually needed leaving none for hundreds of other people. Stores were getting trucks in with NO shipments of water on them. I personally think in a country such as ours that it should be required that enough water be sent to a state where people are under a hurricane watch even if it has to come from other states that are not effected by it. Add this to the hype and over excitement caused by the TV news stations, people at stores were fist fighting, cussing and yelling at one another and just over all being hateful instead of trying to help one another. I believe that TV News is important and it seems to be the MOST utilized means of media, that they have a responsibility to not OVERREACT and get people over emotional. I realize as people they are probably scared too for the same reasons but again, if that is their job, they need to report responsibly. Like I said, many, many people here, myself included, suffer from PTSD from hurricane Charley in 2004. Yes, that was many years ago. Why didn't I move from the area? Because I've never had the financial resources.

Q81:
We were extremely worried about gas availability on the road (word of mouth from friends who had problems finding any/long lines). By luck we stopped to use the restrooms at the Pompano Service Plaza on the Florida Turnpike and decided to top off the gas tank. It was extremely well organized by workers directing traffic to the pumps and we spent a minimal amount of time there. The very next Service Plaza (and every one thereafter) had long lines and signs directing you to go to the next Plaza. The next place we stopped was on 1-10. When we pulled off at an exit on I-10 to fill up again, the gas station on the north side was out of fuel. A Sheriff's car was sitting at the exit to the plaza, so we asked him if there was gas on the south side of the highway. He said he didn't know in a fairly rude tone of voice, which surprised us. We did find one (of four) gas stations on the south side of the exit did have gas available, so were able to fill up.
We did ask an out-of-state relative to help us out by using Gas Buddy, but it really didn't help too much. Mostly we were able to find gas just by pulling off at different exits when we had about 1/4 tank full. 
We carried a 5 gallon gas can with us to extend our range, but never used it.

Q81: Florida was not prepared for the evacuation that was ordered here. Many, many counties all having to leave under the same evacuation plan. A normal 8.5 hour trip took us 18 almost 19 hours to arrive. It was the worst sight on the roadways I had ever seen and questioned many times if we should just turn around and go back. Cars broke down, people on the side of the road sleeping, no gas, cars who had run out of gas, cars with gas cans strapped to the roof of their vehicle. People sound asleep in cars pulled off to the side of the road, exhausted. Rest area lines went on for miles and miles. People literally running for their lives, creating accidents, hostile road ways. I questioned our safety for hours. I questioned our sanity. We live on an Island, in a mandatory evacuation and if I knew then what I know now, I probably would have taken the chance and stayed at home with our family.

Q81:
We stayed home even though we had a hotel reservation in Orlando because the projected track shifted towards my family in Clearwater so I gave them the room instead.  They couldn't evacuate in time so went to a shelter instead.  We didn't know they were doing that until it was too late for us to evacuate.  

We stayed in our house because the wind speed was projected to be a category 2 when it hit.  Didn't know about the continuous tornado warnings we would endure, the sound of the wind hitting out house, and the stress associated with it.  

We stayed in our house even though we lost power at 10:30 AM and at 9 Pm we discovered water was coming in all our doors.  Our garage flooded and water was still rising and coming in the house.  We called the police for help and advice and the operator said they weren't going out on calls.  I called a friend and they came to rescue us from the flooding in a 4x4 truck. We escaped our house through thigh high water with 4 ziplock bags of belongings and a cooler of food for my son with allergies.

  We are all still reacting to any and all storms and are afraid of rain.  Not evacuating was probably the worst decision we've made.

Q81:
My evacuation process was a bit of an ordeal. I traveled alone in my Honda Civic and left quite early wanted to get ahead of major traffic. I am single and live alone so I was the only one that needed to evacuate specifically from my house.   I live just feet away from evacuation zone A on the Indian River Lagoon. I stayed for hurricane Matthew, but Irma seem to be a much more dangerous storm. My dad let me know a few days before the storm hit that he was planning to go to Atlanta to my uncle?s house, but he could not leave until Friday morning around 10 AM. I thought that was too long to wait and I was right. I left at 2 AM on Friday and it took 14 hours to get to Atlanta, and it took my father almost 18 hours For the same trip. The trip up wasn?t Terrible, but it was very tiring traveling with a chronic illness for 14 hours on the road alone. I was dehydrated and stressed out from the traffic.

The ride back on Tuesday was a different story. First, I downloaded the gas buddy app to be sure that I had a resource to find fuel if needed. I made the plan to keep my fuel tank at 3/4 full at all times because of the Traffic. On my way home on interstate 75, I stopped at a gas station in Adel, GA Where a woman came up to me at the gas pumps. She said her husband pulled up to a pump that was out of order and she felt that I needed to give up my pump because they were there first. She was extremely confrontational and I was frightened as I was traveling alone. People were staring because the woman was yelling at me and I didn?t know what to do. Finally, I told her that it was my pump, I was traveling alone as a woman with a chronic illness, and I needed to get fuel and get back on the road. It was a very troubling experience. I don?t think I will ever forget her face. She came at me with such anger. I still can?t understand why anyone would do that, especially to a woman traveling alone.  

The trip back to Florida only took 12 hours in comparison to the 14 hour trip...This was surprising as on my way back into North Florida, Siri routed me onto side roads And I ended up at the back road that had portions flooded. I felt that in my car it was not safe to proceed, but I couldn?t figure out how to get my phone to reroute back to I 75 so I had to use my memory to backtrack to the main highway.

 Again, it was a stressful situation and during future Evacuations I will be cognizant of the fact that Siri is not up to date on where roads are flooded, especially side roads. I also will not travel alone because I really needed someone there to talk to during the long stops in traffic and for safety.  I also plan to get a larger vehicle to where I could transport fuel cans and not have to worry about being stranded without fuel. Or...I could just move out of Florida and no longer have to worry about evacuations.

By traveling the evacuation route out of Florida via interstate 75, I?m perplexed as to why there are not more lanes in Georgia, and why the shoulders of the interstate leading out of Florida are not more readily accessible to vehicles. There should also be more digital billboards giving traffic updates as it is dangerous to constantly check your phone while you?re driving.  There were also some inaccuracies on the delays via my phone?s GPS that would cause unnecessary braking/slowing by others as they expected traffic ahead too.

Q81:
We had a horrible time finding a place to stay that would take dogs.   I contacted Disney World before Irma hit to see if we could bring the dogs there to stay with us.  We were told to evacuate inland since we are on the coast.   Our original plan was to go to Orlando.  Disney said they would not let us keep the dogs in our room and they would have to stay at the kennel,  which we could not afford.    We assumed all of the hotels would have a similar policy, plus most hotels were sold out. 
Also,  we were on the verge of panicking.    Later we found out that all hotels in Florida had to take dogs because of a FEMA rule.   We didn't know about the rule.   We found out after traveling to Pennsylvania.  We went to Pennsylvania because we found out that we could keep the dogs with us at LaQuinta Inns.  The only one we found that we could stay 3-4 days was in PA.  The rest of the LaQuintas were sold out in Tennessee,  Georgia,  Alabama,  and south Carolina.   Also,  a Comfort Inn said we could keep the dogs if we stayed with them,  but we would have to pay $60 per dog per night.  The next hurricane we will probably not evacuate and tough it out.

Q81: We didn't take any chances, at all. We cleared out of Florida before most of everyone I know. They all were nonchalant, but our family takes a natural disaster like this very seriously. It was odd packing up items that couldn't be replaced, going through every box, every drawer, keeping in mind of the worst possibility (for peace of mind while away), that our island home could turn into an inlet like it almost did for Hurricane Matthew... that life went on while Irma was on track to hit Florida for many days before confirmation. Schools were still in session up until Friday, people were still working on Thursday, on into the weekend. It was an eerie feeling, very unsettling. And almost everyone I know, including myself has had almost a post-trauma brain fog for going on several weeks since we got back home. We all had to scatter like ants whose homes were stomped on by someone named Irma, and life goes on. Missing appointments, school projects neglected, flailing around like a live fish on a grill. And we didn't get hit hard AT ALL like the Keys did. Life is fine now, but everyone is so scattered still.

Q81:
Every storm is different, and unpredictable; therefore, every evacuation is different.  Authorities do not want to 'jump the gun'; therefore, they delay ordering evacuations; that causes traffic congestion, especially if the evacuations are widespread across the state -- and Florida just doesn't have enough roads to accommodate all the vehicles involved in major evacuations.  

Major Local issues (still occurring):  
1.  Despite frequent high-wind storms & high-salt conditions, power lines are on top of poles, constantly exposed to the elements; burying the lines would be a much better alternative.

2.  Due to frequent big storms, oversaturation of ground has caused a continuing issue with dumping of sewage/wastewater into/contamination of local rivers (the Indian River Lagoon) & the Atlantic ocean.  Local authorities have announced that residents can cease water conservation efforts, even though the dumping continues, with no plan for a permanent fix.

Q81:
On your survey I answered a question wrong, but it wouldn't go back. We were ordered to stay inside (no emt's would be available). Residences very near us were ordered to evacuate.
     We have 7 children. One is an epileptic, medically fragile, insulin dependant diabetic. When we made plans to evacuate, Irma's forecasted eye path was directly over our home. Though block & sturdy, it is only about 2 miles inland from the Atlantic. We boarded the windows and put sandbags at the doors. The odds of losing power were pretty much 100%, and our kid needs electricity to survive.
     Then, we packed our family pictures, 3 koolers, 10 bags of clothes, (one for each) medicines, insulin, a wheelchair, a toddler potty, the tent, our gun, a bag of balls and gloves for pit stops, each kids favorite thing (from saxaphones to ceramic banks), 5 backpacks full of homeschool textbooks, my camera, 3 tablets, and a partridge in a pear tree. Just kidding, but our van was utterly ridiculous. 
     The major highways were gridlocked & many places out of gas, so we drove on back roads as much as possible, picking up I-10 west of Tallahassee. I used google maps constantly to evaluate our path and we detoured at least 3 times when it was red ahead. We waited in line for an hour to get gas in a tiny town 11 miles off of our route, but it was the only place stocked. The drive that normally would take 8 hours took 22. However, we were moving at 30 mph or greater the entire time. (Except for bathroom breaks and gas lines)
      There was a shared sense of community during the evacuation. People were kinder than usual. I waited in line for a potty break with some Japanese tourists that had been honeymooning at Disney. They were terrified and had no idea where they were going besides away from Irma. 
     Overall, we would do it again and take the same back roads route, using Google maps to assist. (We only had one tiny flub up where it tried to send us down a resident's driveway in backwoods. Nope. U turn.)  22 hours in a car with 7 anxious kids was torturous, but the peace of knowing we were safe when tornados were passing through our neighborhood was worth every minute travelling and every dollar spent.

Q81: One reason why we would likely never evacuate is because it is terribly difficult to get back to your home quickly due to gas shortages and road closures.  You are stuck in a hotel inland that likely also lost power and has windows that do not open.  Also, we live about 5 miles from the intercoastal waterway.  We are not at risk for flooding/storm surge, and we do not take the brunt on the wind.  We live in a relatively new concrete block home built to stringent codes that take hurricanes into account.  If a category 4 or 5 was going to hit us directly, we would consider evacuating. Otherwise, our family evacuating is only taking a hotel room inland from another family who lives beachside or is under mandatory evacuation.  Also, the unpredictability of hurricanes is a factor.  We know several people who evacuated to friends' homes on the west coast of Florida during Irma, then the hurricane changed paths and hit them there!

Q81: We left around 2:30AM for both evacuation and reentry, going from Brevard County FL to Cayce, SC. We had heavy traffic on the way up but we were moving quickly the whole time. Google Maps told us to get off of I-95 and get on I-16 East through Savannah and then stay on back roads in SC, so we did. The whole trip took maybe an hour or two longer than usual. On the way home (2am Tuesday morning), traffic was almost nonexistent and we had no problem. We actually made it home in record time, and this is a trip we make several times a year. We did have a hard time finding gas, food, and working bathrooms.  Waze was helpful. Porta potties at interstate rest areas were in bad shape. We came home to find our house undamaged and our utilities restored. Though we didn?t need to evacuate, I?m glad we did because I didn?t want to put my kids through that trauma and it could have taken much longer to get utilities back. We don?t have a generator. We ended up enjoying a fun long weekend with grandparents and cousins.

Q81:
I'm a former lifelong Caslifornia (San Diego) resident now living in central Florida. While living in San Diego, we llived through 2003 and 2007 wildfires. In general, I don't feel Florida is a better place to live than California and I love California but I have to say, between the disasters we lived through between Caalifornia and Florida... Florida has been impressive in communication and care and safety of its citizens. I'm not a fan of Florida Governor Rick Scott but during the evacuation of Florida due to Irma, he knocked it out of the park. He did a phenomenal job of getting on television early and often, communicated clearly and made it clear this was serious. Roads were a breeze for us to evacuate... tolls suspended. I felt reassured and we were taken care of. We knew what was going on every step of the way. It was incredible how it was handled. 
California wildfires... newscasts we're a disaster. Nobody knew what was going on. Aan entire mountain community in San Diego -Crest- literally burned to the ground whilke the news was busy reporting on an affluent neighborhood in the fire zone. Government agencies inept there during crisis. During wildfires we felt completely all alone, lkeft to fend for ourselves. Florida evacuations we felt safe, we felt like we all had a plan and we were all in it together. I lived through it all, firsthand account. Florida rocked it.

Q81:
I live on a barrier island, so evacuating is common. I retired from a hospital on an island, and we would evacuate patients for just about all Hurricanes. I have rarely (twice in my lifetime) felt that my personal items or the structure of my home were in dire danger.  Each time I evacuate, I swear that I never will do it again. The fear and stress of evacuating outweighs the work involved in sheltering in place. I have permanent shutters that I close and would feel quite safe inside. The only reason why I went inland to my son's house was because I'd just gotten an RV which I was afraid would be damaged, and a friend kept telling me that the storm surge would be bad. As it turned out, Irma came in on the west side of the state, and I live on the east side, so although there was a lot of damage, I could have stayed home, but for worry about the RV. 
In the end result, the worst inconvenience was the loss of power and water after the storm. For these things, the RV turned out to be a lifesaver.

You asked if I would transport and house friends or strangers. The answer is absolutely yes. I have, in fact, taken others to evacuate to my relatives homes in Tallahassee in the north.

In the midst of packing/loading all the belongings I could carry, closing up the office (I was the last person to leave), cleaning out the refrigerator, making sure we had food/water/emergency equipment, filling the cars with gas, wrangling the cat, coordinating with my sister and bro-in-law, convincing my mother-in-law to evacuate with us, putting up plywood and sealing up the house-- it is just difficult to fit in additional tasks. However, given that i live in an evacuation zone on a barrier island-- it is unlikely that anyone would want to evacuate TO my location. And I think it would be irresponsible to encourage it. Q81:
During Matthew (last year), we evacuated all the way to Birmingham, AL. It took us more than 12 hours in traffic-- and honestly that was probably making GOOD time! During Irma, as soon as evacuation looked like a possibility (about a week out), I made hotel reservations inland in Orlando. I reviewed my hotel options and picked a location I felt was on reasonably high ground (let's face it-- it's Florida-- it's all pretty flat), in area with new construction and several hospitals where there would be good services and emergency response. As it turns out, the area we picked has underground power lines-- and the hotel had a parking garage. We will be VERY likely to evacuate there again. We were concerned about whether we were going "far enough", but with the uncertainty in the storm's path and practically the whole state evacuating, we didn't want to risk being on the road longer than necessary. Running out of gas in the path of the storm is the worst POSSIBLE outcome. So we went an hour inland, to a place we felt would be reasonably safe except in the event of a direct hit, and hoped for the best. I work for the military and my place of employment is also on the barrier island. So the base was evacuated too. My husband's employer is on the mainland, but also closed in advance of the storm. 
I felt like there were a lot of great resources and information available-- the county's emergency management on Facebook, their automatic text/twitter notifications, the my employer (the military's) automatic text/twitter notifications, local emergency services feeds, the local TV stations weather and meteorology personnel, and even some of the local "community" pages on facebook. But especially for a lot of the "official" resources, most people just don't seem to be aware of them or take advantage of them. Getting the word out about those resources (and figuring out how to engage the non-tech-savvy) is really critical and could really help improve the communication and evacuation process.

Q81: We were going to evacuate to the west coast, Naples, but the hurricane shifted further west. We can not evaluate to a shelter because of my child with a severe peanut allergy. If you can imagine walking through a mine field then you can imagine what daily life is like for my family. Food is pretty much everywhere. Peanuts are used or processed with so many foods, hygiene (shampoo/conditioner/soap/lotion) products, cleaning products, makeup, crafts and so on. Peanut protein will stay present on surfaces unless cleaned with a soap like Dawn and warm water and certain wipes. What I'm saying, it's safer for our family to stay home and risk a hurricane hitting our home than exposing our toddler to an environment full of peanuts which could kill him.

Q21: The only thing that could have been made more clear, was the order of cities to be evacuated. They should designate zones. However, if it is evacuated in zones, it would help space out the traffic. It should also be made clear that during evacuations, people need to keep the left lanes clear, unless they are passing. People riding in the left lanes and going slower than traffic in the right lanes, is dangerous. And, honestly, annoying. It would help people decide if they are going to evacuate if there was a list of pet friendly places. That was very confusing. Getting records from your vet during an approaching storm is not easy. Q78_10_TEXT: Not everyone treats your home with respect. Some people tend to act as if they don't have to show general respect and common decency. I have let strangers stay in my home for disasters in the past, free of charge. I have experienced both ends of the spectrum. Some people were very respectful and thankful. Others have completely trashed the area where they were staying. And, stolen items from my house. If there was some way that they could be held responsible for any damages or thefts, I wouldn't be as apprehensive about letting strangers stay in my home.
Q81:
I found my experience to be fairly easy. The fact that extra port-o-potties, had been put out at every rest area was very convenient. I only wish they had left them out a little longer for the return trip. I evacuated alone with 2 small dogs. So, the port-o-potties made it easier for me to use the restroom. On my return trip home, I didn't stop as much. The very first time I did stop to use the restroom on my way home, I returned to see someone about to break my window of my car, because my dogs started barking as soon as I got out of my car. With the port-o-potties, I was able to walk my dogs on the way to the line. And, was able to take my dogs in the potty with me. Most rest areas, do not allow dogs around the main building. So, when I had to use the restroom, my dogs had to stay in the car. If they could have port-o-potties available during evacuations and for returning evacuees, that would be so helpful. 
Another suggestion I have is, if southern states could add "service areas", like they have up north. That way, instead of having to exit into a town, you can just go to an area that is more like a rest area. Only, instead of a simple rest area, there are places to get food, use the restroom and, get gas.

Q81:
We evacuated for every storm in 2004. It was horrible. Spent thousands of dollars and got stuck in traffic on the 528.  People don?t realize that there?s only one way out of Florida and the evacuation process is treacherous. We returned to Cocoa Beach to 10 days without power. 

We evacuated for Matthew, and again, it was very expensive. We took care of my elderly parents who could not afford to evacuate. The stress and the news coverage beforehand was almost unbearable. Our home received minor damage. We were lucky. 

We decided not to evacuate for Irma mainly because of the uncertainty of her path. We live on the east coast and the storm kept veering west. It didn?t make sense to go closer to the storm and head right into the belly of the beast.  The size of Irma was overwhelming. We felt that we couldn?t escape her no matter where we went in Florida, so we decided to stay. We live oceanfront and it was the worst night of my life.

Q81: I had just temporarily moved to Florida to be with my mom who is on hospice, and had never been through a hurricane before. My brother, whose house I live in with our mother, had been through a hurricane, but not one predicted to be as severe as Irma. Starting on Monday, September 4, we started prepping for hurricane, and discussing whether or not to evacuate ourselves, our mother, and our two cats. We decided on Wednesday the 6th to stay, because it seemed like Irma would go more east of where we live in Lee County. Then, by the time we found out it was going to directly hit where we lived, there was no way we could evacuate my mother, or go to a shelter with her. So we stayed and hoped for the best. The storm itself was not bad, and we took no damage other than losing electricity for four or five days. I am glad we did not evacuate.

Q81: I live on a barrier island on the Space Coast,  Brevard County. Most of here do not leave for any hurricanes due to the closure of our causeways. It can take days to open the bridges, then you have to get your surfboard or something to paddle across to your home from the mainland. Boats are usually destroyed or washed away so everything is by surfboard and it is just way too expensive and traumatic to sit on the mainland looking at our barrier island and wondering if our home is still there and who is robbing it. Q81: When the hurricane was looking to be a cat 5 hitting the Keys - we left. Knowing how bad traffic would be we left days earlier - North FL hotels only had one night vacancy bc they were already booked up from others making their way up north so we stayed one night after a 7-8hr drive in N FL and the next day headed to GA, not knowing where we were going. Macon was completely booked so between my husband and I (who were each in our own car in fear of leaving a car behind and being totaled from potential flooding) we sat in the parking lot at the Ramada who had no vacancy despite Hotels.com saying they did, we called every place possible and finally found a second rate hotel with enough vacancy in Forsyth, GA. It was a horrible place to stay, but the people of the town were amazing and incredibly friendly. Glued by the tv, we saw our mayor being interviewed and all the evacuation districts. Media did sensationalize quite a bit- we did notice that. When I got a text from a friend who rode out the storm and said it's safe to come back, we did- this was the day after the hurricane hit. What we weren't prepared in was coming back to a state with no food open, no power, no gas and knowing we would be running out. No vacancies anywhere. A friend in Palo Alto figured out my gas % and said I had enough to get to Tampa. After one last final attempt using Gasbuddy, a Speedway was open and we got right in and we're able to fill up and make it back to Fort Myers. We got back to a complete black out, no lights, very dark and disorienting and nothing but massive trees, traffic lights, signs and some structural bldgs down. We had no damage to our property other than lost trees. No power for five days and it was awful, no wind, no a/c, utter heat and humidity. I flew back to Texas the day the airport opened back up (Thursday) and saw Air Force One land (people were so pissed Trump was here, delaying our flights and not really doing anything). I spent another five days with family in San Antonio and Austin (my father died and handling his estate on top of having to give a talk at a conference- also learned catastrophic news the day I evacuated at my work so the whole summer was a mindf$&@ and I found it fitting to end it all with a massive hurricane approaching). My husband stayed with a friend whose power came back on. My research center (clinical trials for Alzheimer's disease) was out of commission and having no power, we lost all of our antibody drugs that required refrigeration (no, this was not the catastrophic news as it was prior). It could have been much worse, so as a first timer going through a hurricane, we learned what we did right and what we need to improve on. Gulf Shore Life did an interview on me. Short but too the point. Forsyth and Macon were a complete eye opener. Here's the brief article: http://www.gulfshorelife.com/Along-the-Gulfshore/September-2017/Hurricane-Stories-Finding-Peace/

Q81: We probably would not have left if we did not have my husband's parents to look out for, especially as we watched the forecast track change and move farther away from us. Q81: Our local family consisted of myself, my husband, my brother, his wife and stepson and my elderly parents age 80 and 86.  My parents home at first was in a voluntary evacuation zone then a mandatory storm surge evacuation zone.  They however absolutely did not want to evacuate.  My husband would not leave our home with fear of not being able to easily return.  My brother's home is in a low area with a lot of trees and he didn't want to bring my parents there.  Originally we were all going to my parents home since they have hurricane windows with the exception of the 6 sliding glass doors.  My parents also did not want to travel or fly to our vacation home in Alabama and we didn't want to get trapped on the highway with no gas or lodging.  Our plans were constantly changing, at one point we were going to meet at a local shelter but several filled up too fast and my mom wouldn't go due to tight quarters and high anxiety.  At 12:30am in the morning Friday, we decided everyone would come to my home.  I have a small house with well water,  everyone arrived Sat around 10am with plenty of food, water, emergency supplies, including a satellite type portable TV, generator and grill.  It was a tight fit but we are family so it was fine.  I called my mom and told her I expected her and Dad to co-operate with my brothers decision since he had kept up with the weather reports every hour.  They finally agreed.  I believe we made the correct decision but in the future, I would send my parents away to our vacation home because the no power for 11 days was way too much for their health even though we were able to run fans with the generator.

Q21: Here's the thing, the evacuation zones that I know that had a mandatory evacuation order was I believe zone 1 which is everywhere east of US 1 to the beaches. I live a mile or 2 from US 1. Now, I'm not meteorologist, buuuuut, when a 400 mile wide Cat 4/5 hurricane is bearing down on the region, and witnessing what it did to the neighboring Island Nations in the Caribbean, I don't think a hurricane adheres to evacuation zones. I decided to pack and protect my place and shut it down and leave to my friend's apartment in West Palm Beach, an hour north from my place and also 15 miles west and more inland. Even when I went to his place, he and his family were planning to drive out west to the gulf coast to get to better shelter. At that time, I was watching all the reports on the news and staying in contact with my work. I remember Thursday Sep 7 seeing reports on the national news outlets stating to "Evacuate Immediately" and "we can't help you in the middle of the storm" and watching the destruction in the Caribbean, I decided I was not going to stay for the storm when it was that close and had no idea what it was going to do when it got here. I was mainly concerned for my well being and ultimately the worst case scenario of being stranded on my own after the damage. I was lucky enough to be able to get a flight out the next day to be with family up North and ride it out. The timing and preparation of evacuating several million people could have been more efficient with more time as it approached. I think the Governor was clear to everyone that he wanted us all to leave or be safe no matter what. The problem came between deciding between mandatory and voluntary, but as I stated before, a 400 mile wide cat4/5 hurricane doesn't care. I think the headache and discomfort of evacuating millions is far better than risking staying and facing destruction. Nobody should be punished for making a decision to protect themselves and their families, the Governor could have communicated that better to employers throughout the state. The region here was lucky and blessed to be spared from the destruction witnessed in the neighboring countries.

Q59_11_TEXT: My car was completely packed with my belongings, there was no space to pick up anyone. Usual commuter trips were multiplied by 3x the typical drive time in during the time of preparation. I drove my friend around once I settled my stuff in his place so he could get a few items. For instance, a trip from here to Orlando is roughly 3 hours. During the lead up to the storm it took a friend 9 hours. Gas was tapped by Wednesday in most places, where there was gas, you could potentially sit and waste an hour just to fill your car up. Having to account for someone else during this time is not an obligation, the primary goal is to protect yourself first. If I had everything settled and protected and deemed myself safe and then saw someone stranded, then is when I would be more open to help. Florida traffic is horrendous on nice non-hurricane days. Florida drivers are the worst in the world. Understand, deviating from the evacuation in the lead up could be life or death IF that storm makes a direct hit.

Q81: Communication from the government to the citizens is not clear and direct. The county which has 6,000+ employees could utilize its resources (personnel) more effectively to reach out to the citizens. When an emergency hits, me personally, I do not look for the government to assist much nor do I expect it nor do I need it. Government is not flexible and is too rigid and restrictive with how it treats its citizens. Not enough leeway to work with the government. All I expect from them is to work with the meteorologists to make a distinct decision on who is at most risk & needs to evacuate and best possible ways to get out and where to go. Announcements on the TV & radio work to a degree, but there should already be a plan in place to communicate to people what best to do. There are many people that move here from elsewhere never experience a hurricane before so the government should never assume its citizens know what and where they need to go. But, they shouldn't hold the citizens' hands, just give a map on where to go. To that extent it is effective. Going out of that reach, it is ineffective and interferes with the process.

Q81:

I called a supposed govt number for an Irma update four different times and it just rang and rang a busy tone. 
 Also, I tried to dial 211 for info on shelters and it was also a busy line. 
I tried to call shelters that were listed withOUT details (pets okay, when opening, food avail, what can i bring, etc etc) on a govt page online. Both were schools and no one answered and it went to voicemail. I left messages and no one ever called back that I am aware of, at any time.  
I think communications and updates could have been FAR improved. 
They should be direct from a govt or other official source, NOT a news station.  I don?t even have TV as a way to save money while in school.  
There should be a way to sign up for auto-alerts and text messages live and direct, from the official source. I would like to have that option.  It would be so helpful vs media and word of mouth.

Q81: My families evacuation process was a disaster. My mother , sister, and I were in Cuba visiting my ill grandparents who have cancer. My father put up shutters on wednesday evening at their house in naples,FL. Later that evening or early thursday the buzz starts going around abut our neighborhood being an evacuation zone and dad had to leave. At first he was a little hesitent because we have 2 little dogs who are our babies and we didnt know who would take him in with the 2 pups. He was thinking of a shelter but had no idea where the shelter for people with dogs were. I end up calling my husband frm cuba to tell him he has to take da in with the pups or go from port charlotte to naples to pick up the dogs. Finally my husband ends up convincing my dad to leave to out home in port charlotte. So he packs up early friday morning I believe around 6 or 7am he was scared stored would hit the area while being on the road so he wanted to leave early to port charlotte. Days prior to leaving naples, their was already no food or water at Walmart. He ended up going at 3am to get gas for the van and waited a mile on the road to finally get there and they ran out of gas. Streets for backed for miles waiting to get in line. And lets not even mention how nasty humans get under pressure we saw many gas station fights over gas. He also stopped to pick my grandparents but hes stubborn as a mule he decided he was gonna stay in naples so dad left them a generator and said good luck.  Once he actually makes it to port charlotte he unpacks his items and the dogs my mother in law already had a room waiting for him. She did a really great job. They decide to go and buy as much food and item as they can find since there were going to be a lot of people and dogs staying in the same place. They also put up boards and shutters on the houses that day. On one of the trips to gather items on the radio they start announcing mandatory evacuation for charlotte county as well as collier county. They decided to go back home and gather with the family to make a decision by the time they make it home. The police was already there. they only had 20mins to pack up everyone and everything including 6 dogs and 2 handycaps. They got whatever they could at the moment and put it in the cars. they also had to stop and pick up family on the road and an elderly neighbor they decided to help and take her to the shelter. Once they finally made it to i75 it took they 14hours to make it to douglass,GA. It was a horrifying seen with 6 dogs stuck on i75 waiting on traffic and an elderly on a wheelchair that has special accommodations. IT was hard bacuse there was no gas so they had to go masive lines. If they found gas for the vans they had to keep looking because not all gas stations had diesel for my husbands truck. No restaurants open not even  mcds so eating on the road was very hard. and the traffic was horrible. When they finally made it we were so relieved to hear that they had finally made it to a safe area. WE were constantly calling until at one point where the signal died and there was no connections from cuba to fl or from ga to fl. We were paying that my grandparentss were okay they were disappeared for 3 days we didnt hear anything from them. Q81:
I am an Emergency Manager and had to work at the EOC prior to and during the hurricane.  We do not live in an evacuation zone.  However, when Irma was projected to be a category 4 or 5 hurricane headed straight toward Broward County, we were seriously considering evacuating my family out of the County (possibly Orlando).  We recalled Hurricane Wilma which caused considerable roof damage to our house and that was just a low category 2 hurricane.  When the hurricane models predicted a more westerly track for Irma, we decided the family would shelter in place.  As it turned out we had virtually no damage (a few screens in the pool enclosure were damaged).  

Broward county's plans call for evacuation from the barrier islands to protect residents from storm surge.  During the initial track predictions, it appeared we would have significant storm surge and a mandatory evacuation was ordered for all residents east of Interstate 1 (Federal Highway), mobile homes, and residents living in areas know to be prone to flooding.  Even though as it turned out the storm took a more westerly track and storm surge was minimal, this was the correct call given the information we had and the timing necessary to implement the evacuation.

Q81: My home did not lose power; however, my friends and family members did lose power and experienced flooding. I allowed my roommate's mother, brother, and dog to use my bedroom and couch. Our other roommate's boss lost power so he, his wife, their dog, and their 2 cats stayed at my home. They stayed at our home for 7 days. I went to my mom's house about a mile away. She did not have power, but she suffers from an illness that causes her to become very upset during situations that change her normal routine. She did not have power for 7 days while I stayed with her. Her home was not prepared for the hurricane at all, and finding food and water after the hurricane passed would have been incredibly difficult if my roommates and I hadn't prepared so well and I was able to bring supplies to their home. My mom ended up so stressed and unwell during this time that she went to the hospital twice. The hospitals were overflowing with homeless people claiming to be sick to have shelter. It could have been worse, but it was an incredibly stressful week.

Q81: The evacuation process is a nightmare. My boyfriend lives on a barrier island and was a mandatory evacuation, he has two cats. I lived at home at the time where my family had three large dogs. We made the choice, since he couldn't have his cats at my house and had to evacuate to leave together. We chose to go back to the panhandle because it appeared to be the only portion of the state that MAY not be hit by the hurricane. At the time we left Irma was headed straight for our home on the East coast of Florida as a Cat 5 and we did not want to take any chances. One day after we arrived in San Destin the hurricane had shifted towards us on the West coast of the state now. It's a terrible situation to be put in because you fret over leaving, worrying if you're making the right choice and knowing you're about to spend thousands of dollars that will be un-reimbursed and then you wake up and the hurricane has followed you and you realize you made the wrong decision and you should have stayed. But in the moment you made the decision it was the right one. You're forced to choose to leave or stay so far in advance of the storm actually arriving that it becomes a coin toss. Overall we were glad we left because his condo on the beach flooded terribly and his cats were safer not in the house but next time, we may just stay.

Q81: We are very limited in Florida regarding evacuation routes.  Roadways are therefore highly congested and get worse the closer the storm comes.  Although tolls are suspended at such times, it would help to commence opening all lanes to route traffic out of the area somewhat earlier.  Those individuals who must remain and travel opposite directions should be routed to alternate roads, thereby freeing up all lanes of interstates for evacuees.  This should commence at the very latest once the projected cone is three days out, if not earlier.  I have a family member who evacuated to the closest available hotel which was in Florence, S.C.  It took him 11.5 hours to drive 400 miles with sections of the road at a complete stand still necessitating leaving the interstate (I-95) and taking back roads.  It could be a death sentence to be stranded on a highway during a storm.

Q81: The most stressful part is preparing your ENTIRE house for evacuation : Board up, bring outside furniture inside, cover furniture with plastic in case of leak, get cash, get gas, get food, get water, pack it all in your car, turn off water main. Does my family or friends need help? Preparing MULTIPLE properties such as for your parents and grandparents who aren't able to put up shutters. The unplanned expense of getting supplies and tools you don't have: hammer drill and drill bits $200+. ALL before the storm comes! Many don't have the flexibility I had to take 2 days off work to prep. Once you finally evacuate, not knowing the status of your home is stressful. Is it damaged? How long would it take to repair? How much? Is there power? Can I safely reach my neighborhood? Was my car damaged or flooded?

Our travel from coastal Brevard County to Seminole County was without problems.  No congestion or other delays at the time we evacuated.  Hotel rooms filled very quickly throughout Florida and earlier than for Hurricane Matthew in 2016.  We assumed that was because of the heightened fear that resulted from the hurricane that had just hit Texas a month or so earlier, and the power of Irma as it approached Florida.
We have special needs and using a public shelter would be a last resort.  The alternative of using a hotel is very expensive.  We've spent about $2000 for hotel rooms for the evacuations associated with Irma and Matthew.

Q81:
Honestly.. The fact that Florida has two major highways in and out is a huge problem when it comes to evacuating. It's nothing but a traffic jam and cars running on empty with no gas in sight. This, coupled with the fact that my mother is disabled and I have a back injury and cannot sit for long periods of time (or sleep just anywhere) were part of our decision. We had family to go to in Orlando but the storm turned and was headed there. Typically our area of the state has never had a direct hit (in 120 years of Hurricane Tracking) so we felt confident that we would get a storm that would be no greater than a Cat 2. Although we did receive wind and rain damage it wad nothing like other parts off the state and we actually slept through the brunt of the storm. We chose not to evacuate the year prior, when governor Scott told us that "we would all DIE" (yes. He actually said that on the news) if we did not evacuate for Matthew. Matthew wss definitely a stronger, more direct hit than Irma. With greater tree loss. However... We were fine then too. I feel there needs to be a fine balance between public safety and public panic which we saw a great deal of during Irma. Much of that I believe was a factor because of Harvey having just occurred in Houston. Anyway.. If you research it, you'll find that most residents did not evacuate here on the Island we live in (barrier island.. Merritt Island)...on my street alone only one house did. (To Orlando where they got hit worse)
I also had friends drive to Tampa and then end up returning here when the eye of Irma turned.

Q81:
My husband stayed to watch the house and pets, along with my 20 yr old. I left with the two young children and strong request of my father who lives in New England. He sent money for the hotel and gas otherwise I would not have been able to go. Hotels were booked all the way through Georgia and I finally decided on the 800 mile trip. Getting there was a long drive. Hundreds of accidents and many hours added on due to reroutings, which were beautiful by the way! Residents in the back roads stood outside and offered free food and drink in places and one church was offering lodging and food for the displaced on the road.
The hotel was great (Hampton Inn)! A local church brought in 50 pizzas, snacks, and drinks the first night there. We shouldn't have left three days later, but we're out of money and thought things would be fine when we returned.
The ride home took 26 hours. Accidents cluttered the highest every few miles. I found one hotel with a room open only to find it to be the equivalent of a sex trafficking hotel. I left with the children after being told my money wouldn't be refunded for days, leaving me with no sleep, on dark roads, hungry and weary.
Not one of the hundreds of churches we passed were offering assistance. Not ONE. I stopped at two serious rest stops to grab a couple hours of sleep at a time, sitting up... Car running...doors locked. I refilled my gas tank where I could but most places were out of gas, food, coffee, and even toilet paper. One place had septic backed up into the store and they just kept raking it out the front door. One rest stop had porta potties did into a hill with a water reservoir right below. By sunrise the second morning, my son was vomiting from eating nothing but crap snacks that we could find.
We finally made it home to no water and no power. It was 100 degrees. We spent much time in the car, running the A/C and driving around looking for food, water, and milk. Nothing was to be found. When the water came on a few days later, it was still undrinkable. We took cold showers because we are all electric. My oldest son, who is autistic, stated to become withdrawn. I heard about FEMA hotel rooms and applied. I was approved and immediately went to the hotel. We were in and out, and back and forth for days... Maybe a week. The kids school reopened. My five year old daughter started having anxiety attack for the first time in her life. 
The power company was so negligent and difficult, I have joined class action law suit. It took TEN DAYS for our power to be restored. Our nephew in the country waited 26 days.
Our rental home is newer and made of steel and block and made it through the storm undamaged. We had none of the expected flooding. 
The hurricane was dealable.
The power, water, food, and emergency management was horrendous. Awful. Horrible.
The roads getting out and back... Pure hell on Earth.

Q26_14_TEXT: Checked on a hotel in north GA but was told that I may need to leave if the storm came up there(which it did). We have 2 rescue dogs that would have been traumatized by being locked in a cage in a separate room as the shelters here require. Shelters also only give you a spot on the floor of a building that is not as safe as my house. We are old and disabled and would have great difficulty bringing the food,meds, bedding, etc. (for both humans AND pets). Plus the dogs and I are fearful of crowds and noise. Plus, my house is reinforced concrete block, with concrete poured in, all the roof rafters have the metal straps, even the shingles are reinforced (we didn't lose ANY)! I saw my PCP the day before the evac, and he asked if we were going/staying. When I told him where I live he responded that he grew up on the next street over, knew what the houses are like, and he said,"That house is a bunker, you'll be fine"!

Q81: I watched the hurricane progress and had a good idea of when it would make landfall in Florida. I made hotel reservations (Valdosta Ga) 5 days out from landfall from experience.  Initally we decided to evacuate due to the possibility of losing powrr, contaminated water, and wind damage. Life and comfort are more important than replaceable items. We evacuated to my parents in St. Marys Ga to evacuate with them to Valdosta, when tge hurricane changed course and was predicted to go over Valdosta we stayed put.  Regardless, we had high winds and rains since we were in the eastern quadrant of the storm. We lost power for 5 days before we decided to go home. The waterfront area of my parents town was destroyed, without a direct hit. Once we arrived home to Melbourne Do, we survayed the damage, which was minimal. We had power but no air conditioning. Every single grocery store was empty, everything gone. So we tried to find something open, we got lucky. We used the Waze App to find gas and avoid traffic, which we did. We pre plan before the hurricane season ends. Hope this helps

Q81:
Evacuation traffic preparedness: As major evacuation routes, Florida highways (interstates and turnpike) must have more lanes. And during evacuations, police need to direct and control traffic on the shoulders of he roads, entry and exit ramps, rest stops and especially cars trying to access gas stations near ramps. We exited the higheay and got stuck due to cars blocking interstate access in lines to get gas. It took four hours to drive 1 mile!! We were afraid for our lives and safety on the roads - drivers went northbound in open southbound lanes with cars traveling them!! Drivers went at high spoeds on road shoulders and there was a lot of panicked and aggressive driving along FL routes. We saw people broken down or out of gas who just had to abandon cars. We saw scores of vehicles left running on highway shoulders overnight while occupants tried to sleep. And we were aware that they were panicked and TIRED drivers out there - scary. Also, we had to drive for about 24 hours without a hotel stop because the evacuations were so far north. (Highway exit ramps were actually closed wth barriers and cars were forced to go on.)
At the point we evacuated, were expecting a Cat 4 or 5 direct strike in the direction of our home and decided to get ahead of the worst of road and weather conditions.

Q17: I live in Zone C in Miami-Dade County. Only part of Zone C was under a mandatory evacuation notice. The news, radio, and distribution of Miami Dade County?s social media was unclear what part of Zone C was in the mandatory evacuation. At first, it was announced the whole zone was being evacuated, then it announced only part of the zone was being evacuation The map that was being used was difficult to enlarge on a mobile phone, which is primarily how I access the internet. I had to ask my friends and family, and consult with the desktop version of the map to see if I was in the part of the zone receiving the mandatory evacuation. I was. I checked FIU?s storm surge map under category 5 storm surge conditions, as that is what we were anticipating. Upon seeing that my neighborhood would be under 6-12 feet of water, I evacuated to Zone of E of Miami-Dade County, which was not under a mandatory evacuation. It was complicated to determine whether I would be safe if I evacuated to a different part of Miami. I have lived in Miami my whole life and I never received an evacuation notice, even during Hurricane Andrew.  The access to internet on my phone was extremely slow due to everyone else using their data to track the storm.

Q81:
The evacuation was hard but getting back was just a horrible experience. We had to drive through the remains of Irma when it was a tropical storm Monday morning in Alabama and Georgia, in order to get back for my husband's job.  Because of the storm there were no gas stations the whole day, even using the GasBuddy app --the info wasn't accurate, there was no gas anywhere.  We made it to Gainesville Monday around 5 p.m. and were forced to stop for the night because we were almost out of gas. Finding a hotel was hard, nothing was available on Orbitz but we did find one calling around town.  Finding a place to get a hot meal was difficult but we figured that out too just before the curfew went into effect.  The next morning my husband drove around Gainesville looking for gas while I watched the kids at the hotel.  I called around and found a single station that had gotten a shipment earlier--he waited 2 hours to fill up.  After he picked us up at the hotel we didn't stop at all, there were gas stations on the turnpike but we wanted to make it back on one tank because there was at least 2-3 hours wait on those lines, we didn't even stop for the restroom to conserve gas and also because the lines in the rest areas along the turnpike spanned for a few miles before the exits.  I had food and water for the family so we just hunkered in and drove, I believe it took 6 hours from Gainesville. We
 returned on Tuesday and the entire day residents hadn't been allowed into our city (sunny isles beach) but thankfully it had opened back up.  I guess they had shut down some of the shelters at 5 a.m and told people to go home, and then they couldn't get back in to sunny isles because the city had shut it down--it didn't reopen until Tuesday afternoon. People were sleeping in their cars and hotels were booked up from workers being in town for the aftermath and evacuees.  I think the port reopened to deliver gas that evening or the next day, but if we had waited for that it would've been too late--my husband had to be at work Wednesday and would have lost his job.  And after the evacuation that would have been financially devastating.   It was exhausting and expensive.  

When we got home Tuesday night our power was on and we hadn't lost power the whole storm.  However FPL was doing repairs and cut our power in these repairs on Saturday 9/17. Rather than fix it immediately they put us in the back of the line for repairs. We were without power from Saturday-Wednesday afternoon, with my husband having work and one of my kids having to be at school.  I had to drive around those days finding air conditioning taking care of my younger son and also checking to see if our power was back on. We lost all the food in our fridge and freezer. It was hard to find hotels and we would be in a different hotel every night, checking out in the morning hoping that would be the day the power would come back on. We tried sleeping at our condo one night and it was unbearable, and I was worried about the kids the whole time.  Again neighbors with less financial means were sleeping in their cars, families with children--one of my elderly neighbors had to go to the hospital for heat exhaustion--the heat index topped 100 every day during that time.  

So to sum up I felt like the whole thing was ok as far as getting people out and to safety was concerned, but the aftermath was a complete failure on all fronts.  We took a big financial hit and didnt qualify for help from FEMA.  We experienced a lot of hardship, which pales in comparison to what others in my city experienced as a result of the evacuation and aftermath of Irma.  Also the storm didn't directly hit us, it damaged some signs and took out a lot of trees and some power to some buildings.  I can't imagine what would have happened if it hit us directly.  I feel completely unprepared for next hurricane season and that there's nothing I can do to prepare for a situation like this again.  I had all the supplies and checklists and it helped for a smooth evacuation but not for the aftermath.
